qas.question: What term is given to the Head of Music?
What is an example of a lesser-known instrument taught at Eton?

context: The current <a0_0>"Precentor"<a0_0/> (Head of Music) is <a2_0><b4_0><b5_0><b7_0>Tim Johnson<b7_0/><b5_0/><b4_0/><a2_0/>, and the School boasts <a3_0>eight<a3_0/> organs and an entire building for music (performance spaces include the School Hall, the Farrer Theatre and two halls dedicated to music, the Parry Hall and the Concert Hall). Many instruments are taught, including obscure ones such as the <a1_0>didgeridoo<a1_0/>. The School participates in many national competitions; many pupils are part of the National Youth Orchestra, and the School gives scholarships for dedicated and talented musicians. A former Precentor of the college, <b6_0><b8_0>Ralph Allwood<b8_0/><b6_0/> set up and organised Eton Choral Courses, which run at the School every summer.
